<subSubSection id="DDB876D87A2AFFFFFDCE456F7C77F15A" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="951D25537A2AFFFFFDCE456F7C77F15A" blockId="7.[181,1424,530,1116]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<heading id="CE55923F7A2AFFFFFDCE456F7C3FF11C" allCaps="true" box="[567,1038,530,551]" centered="true" fontSize="7" level="3" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" reason="4">KEY TO CULTIVATED POTATO LANDRACES</heading>
The following key and descriptions, modified from 
<bibRefCitation id="F13358A27A2AFFFFFD43454C7BFDF17F" author="Huaman Z &amp; Spooner DM" box="[698,972,561,580]" journalOrPublisher="American Journal of Botany" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" pagination="947 - 965" part="89" refId="ref34879" refString="Huaman Z, Spooner DM. 2002. Reclassification of landrace populations of cultivated potatoes (Solanum sect. Petota). American Journal of Botany 89: 947 - 965." title="Reclassification of landrace populations of cultivated potatoes (Solanum sect. Petota)" type="journal article" year="2002">Huamán &amp; Spooner (2002)</bibRefCitation>
, highlight typical traits. The qualifier terms ‘mostly’ or ‘usually’ could be employed throughout the key, but are not used for simplicity.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DDB876D87A2AFFFFFF4C45087DA1F767" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" type="key">
<key id="E13372627A2AFFFFFF4C45087DA1F767" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<keyStep id="2E563DF67A2AFFFFFF4C45087DA1F1C6" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<paragraph id="951D25537A2AFFFFFF4C45087DBEF1F9" blockId="7.[181,1424,530,1116]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<keyLead id="2E5386667A2AFFFFFF4C45087DBEF1F9" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
1. Plants semi-rosette to semi-erect; pedicel articulation indistinct to only slightly distinct, located in the upper one-fifth of the pedicel; frost tolerant (of putative hybrid origin with the frost-tolerant species 
<taxonomicName id="52A25ED07A2AFFFFFB1245EF7D7FF19E" box="[1259,1358,658,677]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="acaule">
<emphasis id="A7D6F9417A2AFFFFFB1245EF7D7FF19E" box="[1259,1358,658,677]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">S. acaule</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName id="52A25ED07A2AFFFFFA8345EF79B6F1F9" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="megistacrolobum">
<emphasis id="A7D6F9417A2AFFFFFA8345EF79B6F1F9" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">S. megistacrolobum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
)...............................................................................................................................2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="951D25537A2AFFFFFF4C45B07DA1F1C6" blockId="7.[181,1424,530,1116]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<keyLead id="2E5386667A2AFFFFFF4C45B07DA1F1C6" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">1. Plants ascending to erect; pedicel articulation evident, located below the upper one-fifth of the pedicel; generally not frost tolerant...............................................................................................................................4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="2E563DF67A2AFFFFFF4C447A7DBEF00C" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<paragraph id="951D25537A2AFFFFFF4C447A7DA1F021" blockId="7.[181,1424,530,1116]" box="[181,1424,775,794]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<keyLead id="2E5386667A2AFFFFFF4C447A7DA1F021" box="[181,1424,775,794]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
2. Most distal lateral leaβets broadly decurrent; plants diploid.........................................1. 
<taxonomicName id="52A25ED07A2AFFFFFB43447A7D0DF021" box="[1210,1340,775,794]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="ajanhuiri">
<emphasis id="A7D6F9417A2AFFFFFB43447A7D0DF021" box="[1210,1340,775,794]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">S. ajanhuiri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="0D9939D67A2AFFFFFAB4447A7DB6F021" box="[1357,1415,775,794]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="8.[144,223,1735,1754]" captionTargetBox="[210,1360,195,1704]" captionTargetId="figure-0@8.[208,1360,195,1704]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figure 1. Lectotype specimen of Solanum ajanhuiri Juz. &amp; Bukasov held in WIR (note spelling of specific epithet on this sheet, see text). Reproduced with permission of the N. I. Vavilov Institute of Plant Industry." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6326422" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6326422/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
)
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="951D25537A2AFFFFFF4C44597DBEF00C" blockId="7.[181,1424,530,1116]" box="[181,1423,804,824]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<keyLead id="2E5386667A2AFFFFFF4C44597DBEF00C" box="[181,1423,804,824]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">2. Most distal lateral leaβets not or only slightly decurrent; plants triploid or pentaploid..................................3</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="2E563DF67A2AFFFFFF4C443F7DBEF049" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<paragraph id="951D25537A2AFFFFFF4C443F7DA1F06E" blockId="7.[181,1424,530,1116]" box="[181,1424,834,853]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<keyLead id="2E5386667A2AFFFFFF4C443F7DA1F06E" box="[181,1424,834,853]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
3. Plants low growing, 
<quantity id="525A88B67A2AFFFFFE4B443F7A24F06E" box="[434,533,834,853]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" metricValueMax="9.8" metricValueMin="6.2" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" unit="cm" value="80.0" valueMax="98.0" valueMin="62.0">62–98 cm</quantity>
tall; triploid..............................................................3. 
<taxonomicName id="52A25ED07A2AFFFFFB50443F7D0DF06E" box="[1193,1340,834,853]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="juzepczukii">
<emphasis id="A7D6F9417A2AFFFFFB50443F7D0DF06E" box="[1193,1340,834,853]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">S. juzepczukii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="0D9939D67A2AFFFFFAB4443F7DB6F06E" box="[1357,1415,834,853]" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="13.[164,243,1842,1861]" captionTargetBox="[245,1363,193,1812]" captionTargetId="figure-0@13.[245,1363,193,1812]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figure 3. Lectotype specimen of Solanum juzepczukii Bukasov held in WIR (WIR-36897). Reproduced with permission of the N. I. Vavilov Institute of Plant Industry." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6326426" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6326426/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
)
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="951D25537A2AFFFFFF4C44227DBEF049" blockId="7.[181,1424,530,1116]" box="[181,1423,863,882]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<keyLead id="2E5386667A2AFFFFFF4C44227DBEF049" box="[181,1423,863,882]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
3. Plants of medium height, 
<quantity id="525A88B67A2AFFFFFE1744227A6FF049" box="[494,606,863,882]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.105" metricValueMax="1.25" metricValueMin="0.96" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" unit="cm" value="110.5" valueMax="125.0" valueMin="96.0">96–125 cm</quantity>
tall; pentaploid.................................................2. 
<taxonomicName id="52A25ED07A2AFFFFFB5244227D0DF049" authorityName="Lechn. (Lekhnovich" authorityYear="1983" box="[1195,1340,863,882]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="curtilobum">
<emphasis id="A7D6F9417A2AFFFFFB5244227D0DF049" box="[1195,1340,863,882]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">S. curtilobum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="0D9939D67A2AFFFFFAB444227DB8F049" box="[1357,1417,863,882]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="11.[164,243,1842,1861]" captionTargetBox="[298,1308,193,1812]" captionTargetId="figure-0@11.[298,1308,193,1812]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 2. Lectotype specimen of Solanum curtilobum Juz. &amp; Bukasov held in LE. Reproduced with permission of the V. L. Komarov Botanical Institute." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6326424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6326424/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
)
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="2E563DF67A2AFFFFFF4C44017DA1F0DC" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<paragraph id="951D25537A2AFFFFFF4C44017DBEF097" blockId="7.[181,1424,530,1116]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<keyLead id="2E5386667A2AFFFFFF4C44017DBEF097" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
4. Plants adapted to short-day βowering and tuberization; upper leaves diverged from stem at 40°–50°; diploid, triploid or tetraploid ................................................................... 4. 
<taxonomicName id="52A25ED07A2AFFFFFC1144E77CC6F097" authority="Andigenum" authorityName="Andigenum" box="[1000,1271,921,941]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tuberosum">
<emphasis id="A7D6F9417A2AFFFFFC1144E77CC6F097" box="[1000,1271,921,941]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">S. tuberosum Andigenum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (
<figureCitation id="0D9939D67A2AFFFFFAB544E47DB9F097" box="[1356,1416,921,940]" captionStart="Figure 4" captionStartId="15.[164,243,1842,1861]" captionTargetBox="[286,1322,193,1812]" captionTargetId="figure-0@15.[286,1322,193,1812]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figure 4. Lectotype specimen of Solanum tuberosum L. (Chilotanum group) held in LINN (LINN 248.12). Reproduced with permission of the Linnean Society of London." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6326428" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6326428/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
)
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="951D25537A2AFFFFFF4C44CA7DA1F0DC" blockId="7.[181,1424,530,1116]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<keyLead id="2E5386667A2AFFFFFF4C44CA7DA1F0DC" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">4. Plants adapted to long-day βowering and tuberization; upper leaves diverged from stem at angle of 50°–90°...... ..................................................................................................................................................... 5</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<keyStep id="2E563DF67A2AFFFFFF4C448C7DA1F767" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<paragraph id="951D25537A2AFFFFFF4C448C7DA1F73F" blockId="7.[181,1424,530,1116]" box="[181,1424,1009,1029]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<keyLead id="2E5386667A2AFFFFFF4C448C7DA1F73F" box="[181,1424,1009,1029]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
5. Landrace populations native to south-central 
<collectingCountry id="EDB565C37A2AFFFFFD39448C7AC9F73F" box="[704,760,1009,1028]" name="Chile" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Chile</collectingCountry>
..........................4. 
<taxonomicName id="52A25ED07A2AFFFFFC1D448C7CC6F73F" authority="Chilotanum" authorityName="Chilotanum" box="[996,1271,1009,1028]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tuberosum">
<emphasis id="A7D6F9417A2AFFFFFC1D448C7CC6F73F" box="[996,1271,1009,1028]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">S. tuberosum Chilotanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (
<figureCitation id="0D9939D67A2AFFFFFAB4448C7DB9F73F" box="[1357,1416,1009,1028]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="18.[144,223,1842,1861]" captionTargetBox="[231,1337,193,1812]" captionTargetId="figure-0@18.[231,1337,193,1812]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figure 5. Lectotype specimen of Solanum andigenum Juz. &amp; Bukasov (Solanum tuberosum L. Andigenum group) held in LE. Reproduced with permission of the V. L. Komarov Botanical Institute." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6326430" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6326430/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
)
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="951D25537A2AFFFFFF4C43737DA1F767" blockId="7.[181,1424,530,1116]" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
<keyLead id="2E5386667A2AFFFFFF4C43737DA1F767" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">
5. Modern varieties originally derived from breeding populations in the Northern Hemisphere, now grown worldwide; of many complex hybrid origins from the 
<taxonomicName id="52A25ED07A2AFFFFFD7243517B39F704" box="[651,776,1068,1087]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="chilotanum">
<emphasis id="A7D6F9417A2AFFFFFD7243517B39F704" box="[651,776,1068,1087]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Chilotanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="52A25ED07A2AFFFFFCC643517B89F704" box="[831,952,1068,1087]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="andigenum">
<emphasis id="A7D6F9417A2AFFFFFCC643517B89F704" box="[831,952,1068,1087]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">Andigenum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
groups and other cultivar groups bred up to the earlier 20th century.............................................................4. 
<taxonomicName id="52A25ED07A2AFFFFFC2343347C56F767" authority="L." box="[986,1127,1097,1116]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" pageId="7" pageNumber="114" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="tuberosum">
<emphasis id="A7D6F9417A2AFFFFFC2343347C56F767" box="[986,1127,1097,1116]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="114">S. tuberosum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
relatively modern varieties
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
</key>
